ers cannot stifle the strong, perhaps irresistible, economic, social, and political pressures that fuel international migration.Controversially, Johnson suggests that open borders are entirely consistent with efforts to prevent terrorism that have dominated immigration enforcement since the events of September 11, 2001. More liberal migration, he suggests, would allow for full attention to be paid to the true dangers to public safety and national security.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEmigration and immigration lawzUnited States. 0aIllegal immigrationxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aNoncitizensxGovernment policyzUnited States. 7aLAW / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aFloodgates.  aOpening.  aborder.  acase.  aconstruct.  acountry.  aeliminating.  aimpedes.  ainto.  alegal.  amakes.  amovement.  apeople.  athat.  athis.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081474286040uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814743607.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814743607423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814743607/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK